00:01:56.420 --> 00:02:01.690
blame European brutality, which was definitely
a factor, but the main culprit was disease.

00:02:01.690 --> 00:02:04.479
Smallpox is usually seen as the villain of
the story but it is more likely that a series

00:02:04.479 --> 00:02:08.259
of diseases in combination did the damage.
Along with smallpox, Americans were killed

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:13.349
by measles and mumps, typhus, chicken pox,
none of which they had been previously exposed

00:02:13.349 --> 00:02:18.329
to. This astonishing decrease of population
was definitely the worst effect of these diseases,

00:02:18.329 --> 00:02:20.819
both psychologically and demographically.

00:02:20.819 --> 00:02:24.609
But the secondary effects were almost as bad.
For one thing the deaths of Aztec and Incan

00:02:24.609 --> 00:02:28.999
rulers touched off wars which made it easier
to spread disease, because you know, the number

00:02:28.999 --> 00:02:33.779
one way to catch smallpox is via hand-to-hand
combat. Plus leaders kept dying. Huayna Capac,

00:02:33.779 --> 00:02:38.230
the leader of the Incan empire, succumbed
to smallpox before Pizarro even arrived. His

00:02:38.230 --> 00:02:41.599
death led to a violent succession struggle
between his sons which was won by Atahualpa,

00:02:41.599 --> 00:02:45.639
who in turn was captured and killed by Pizarro.
And without that war, the Inca would have

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:49.499
had a much better chance against the Spaniards,
whose numbers were comparatively tiny. A similar

00:02:49.499 --> 00:02:53.340
thing happened to the Aztecs. The Moctezuma
who eventually lost to Cortés was the nephew

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:58.010
of a much more powerful king who died of smallpox.
And the death of that great king encouraged

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:02.480
some of the smaller states in the Aztec empire to rebel,
and some of them even fought for the Spaniards.

00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:06.280
And another effect of disease was starvation,
because there simply weren't enough people

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:10.169
left to grow crops to feed the living. And
the malnutrition made survivors that much

00:03:10.169 --> 00:03:13.359
more susceptible to disease. In short, it
sucked.

00:03:13.359 --> 00:03:17.680
The transmission of disease largely went one
way, from the Old World to the New, but the

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:23.849
Americans did have one gift for Europe: venereal
syphilis. It showed up in Europe around 1493,

00:03:23.849 --> 00:03:27.519
and even though Europeans are very fond of
ascribing syphilis to each other: Italians

00:03:27.519 --> 00:03:31.419
called it the French disease; the French called
it the disease of Naples; Poles called it

00:03:31.419 --> 00:03:35.549
the German disease; Russians called it the
Polish disease. The truth is, venereal syphilis

00:03:35.549 --> 00:03:37.909
was spread by sailors who'd returned from
the Americas.

00:03:37.909 --> 00:03:41.620
In fact, in his book, The Columbian Exchange,
Crosby tells it like this: "Sailors, by the

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:46.559
nature of their profession, are men without
women and therefore men of many women. We

00:03:46.559 --> 00:03:50.620
can imagine no group more perfectly suited
for guaranteeing that venereal syphilis would

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:54.769
have worldwide distribution." Who says history
books are boring? Syphilis would go on to

00:03:54.769 --> 00:03:58.959
