I mean until 500 years ago Italians lived
without tomatoes, without modern pizza or

00:08:00.259 --> 00:08:06.949
marinara sauce or pizza or ketchup or pizza
or even pizza. Indians lived without curry,

00:08:06.949 --> 00:08:10.889
which contains chilies, a New World food.
Persians lived without corn, which is a New

00:08:10.889 --> 00:08:15.569
World food, as are beans and potatoes and
avocados and peanuts and blueberries - the

00:08:15.569 --> 00:08:16.759
list goes on and on.

00:08:16.759 --> 00:08:20.310
And these New World crops led to probably
the greatest population increase in history.

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:24.800
To quote Crosby, "It is crudely true that
if man's caloric intake is sufficient, he

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:28.610
will somehow stagger to maturity, and he will
reproduce."

00:08:28.610 --> 00:08:32.320
And New World food was far more caloric than
Old World food, which is the central reason

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:37.690
that the world population doubled between
1650 and 1850. Plants like corn and potatoes

00:08:37.690 --> 00:08:41.720
could grow in soils that were useless for
Old World crops. Potatoes were actually introduced

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:45.190
to Europe as an aphrodisiac, but it turns
out that you have to distill those potatoes

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:49.100
into vodka before they have the desired effect.
Anyway, if potatoes are an aphrodisiac, the

00:08:49.100 --> 00:08:51.380
Irish quickly became the hottest people on
Earth.

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:55.770
An acre and a half of potato cultivation could
feed an Irish family for a year, and the average

00:08:55.770 --> 00:09:02.560
Irish worker often ate 10 lbs. of potatoes
every day. Surviving primarily on potatoes,

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:07.940
the Irish more than doubled their population
between 1754 and 1845, when the Potato Famine

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:09.440
showed up and ruined everything.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:13.230
And it wasn't just Europe. Manioc, or cassava
is a New World plant with roots that provide

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:18.140
more calories than any other plant on Earth,
provided they are properly processed (otherwise

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:21.810
they're poisonous). Manioc is so prevalent
in Africa that many Africans swear that the

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:23.580
plant is native to the continent, but it isn't.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:27.330
Nor are sweet potatoes, and while New World
grains never replaced rice in Southeast, or

00:09:27.330 --> 00:09:30.780
East Asia, the sweet potato was so common
that it is known as the "poor person’s staple"

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.500
in China. Even in Japan, the tomb of the farmer
who is reputed to have first brought them

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:38.290
to the islands is known as the Temple of the
Sweet Potato. And it's also worth noting that

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:41.930
corn, while it may not feature prominently
in European diets, has been the central source

00:09:41.930 --> 00:09:44.360
of food for animals in Europe for centuries.

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:50.010
And in fact, that's still the case. In 2005,
58% of the corn grown in America went to animal

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:52.160
feed (is the kind of thing you learn when
you live in Indiana).

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:55.450
Alright, so last but not least, the Columbian
exchange involved the transfer of lots of

00:09:55.450 --> 00:10:00.260
people. Again, in the early stages this movement
was mostly one way, with Europeans and Africans

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:03.420
- the Africans usually against their will
- making their way to the Americas.

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:07.390
So the Columbian Exchange led to the re-population
of the New World following the disease devastation

00:10:07.390 --> 00:10:10.530
of the initial encounter. And better nutrition
allowed the population of the Old World to

00:10:10.530 --> 00:10:14.480
grow which in turn placed population pressure
on Eurasia which led to more people coming

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:18.060
to the Americas. In the process, the world's
human inhabitants became more genetically

00:10:18.060 --> 00:10:21.710
and ethnically interconnected. But it also
led to the horrors of Atlantic slavery, which

00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:22.870
we'll be discussing next week.

00:10:22.870 --> 00:10:26.580
What are we to make of the Columbian Exchange?
It devastated the population of the Americas,

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:30.580
it led to the widespread slavery of Africans,
but it also allowed for a worldwide population

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:34.640
increase and the lives of some Natives including
Plains tribes like the Lakota became better

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:36.950
and more secure, at least for a while.

00:10:36.950 --> 00:10:40.140
Fewer people have starved since the Columbian
Exchange began, but the diversity of life on

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:44.640
Earth has diminished dramatically and planting crops
where they don't belong has hurt the environment.

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:47.970
So on the whole, should we be grateful for
the Columbian Exchange? And should we work

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:51.440
to continue and deepen its legacy of globalism
and monoculture?

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:55.410
Crosby didn't think we were better off. "The
Columbian Exchange has included man, and he

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:59.970
has changed the Old and New Worlds sometimes
inadvertently, sometimes intentionally, often

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:04.920
brutally. It is possible that he and the plants
and animals he brings with him have caused

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:09.620
the extinction of more species of life forms
in the last four hundred years than the usual

00:11:09.620 --> 00:11:13.940
processes of evolution might kill off in a
million... The Columbian Exchange has left

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:19.230
us with not a richer but a more impoverished
genetic pool. We, all of the life on the planet,

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:22.740
are the less for Columbus, and the impoverishment
will increase."

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:26.600
But let's give you the last word today: Do
you agree with Crosby? Are longer, healthier

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:31.330
lives for more humans worth the sacrifice
of an impoverished biosphere? And most importantly,

00:11:31.330 --> 00:11:35.420
how will your conclusions about those questions
shape the way that you live your life?

